  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Establishes international guidelines and best practices\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides frameworks for combating financial crimes\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets standards for banking regulations and anti-money laundering practices\n\n5. Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- International network for information sharing between financial intelligence agencies\n\n6. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Binding regulations for EU member states\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
